    <main>
        <!--First Section-->
        <section id="section1">
            <h2>What is a power system?</h2>
            <p>In fiction, a
            power system is the set of rules,
            limitations, and mechanics that
            govern how characters use supernatural
            or extraordinary abilities. It is the
            "physics" of the impossible within a story's
            universe.</p>

            <p>A well-constructed power system prevents
                the plot from feeling like a series of
                convenient miracles. Instead, it creates
                tension because the audience understands
                exactly what a character can and cannot
                do.</p>

            <hr style="width: 80%; margin-left: 0;">    
        </section>

        <!--Second Section-->
        <section id="section2">
            <h2>1. Hard vs. Soft Power Systems</h2>

            <p>The most common way to categorize these
                systems is by how clearly the rules are
                defined for the audience.</p>

            <ul>
            <li><p><b>Hard Power Systems:</b> These have strict,
                explicit rules. The reader knows the cost,
                the source, and the limits of the power.
                This allows for logical problem-solving.</p>
            </li>

                <ul>
                <li><P>Example: Fullmetal Alchemist's Alchemy.
                It follows the Law of Equivalent Exchange:
                to gain something, something of equal
                value must be lost.</P>
                </li>
                </ul>

                <img src="image1.jpg" alt="IMAGE 1" width="500" height="">

            <li><p><b>Soft Power Systems:</b> These are mysterious and
                vague. The rules aren't fully explained, which
                preserves a sense of wonder or dread.</p>
            </li>

                <ul>
                <li><p>Example: The Lord of the Rings. We know
                Gandalf is powerful, but we don't know
                the exact "MP cost" or limit of his spells.
                </p>
                </li>
                </ul>

                <img src="image2.jpg" alt="IMAGE 1" width="500" height="">

            </ul>

            <hr style="width: 80%; margin-left: 0;"> 
        </section>

        <!--Third Section-->
        <section id="section3">
            <h2>2. Core Components of a Power System</h2>

            <p>For a system to feel "real" to the
                reader, it usually includes these four elements:</p>

            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Component</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                    <th>Example</th>
                </tr>

                <tr>
                    <td><b>Source</b></td>
                    <td>Where the energy comes from.</td>
                    <td>Mana, Qi, Sunlight, Radiation, Genetic Mutation.</td>
                </tr>

                <tr>
                    <td><b>Method</b></td>
                    <td>How the power is channeled.</td>
                    <td>Spells, Martial Arts, Technology, Hand Signs.</td>
                </tr>

                <tr>
                    <td><b>Cost</b></td>
                    <td>The price of using the power.</td>
                    <td>Exhaustion, Sanity, Physical Pain, Lifespan.</td>
                </tr>

                <tr>
                    <td><b>Limits</b></td>
                    <td>What the power cannot do.</td>
                    <td>Cannot bring back the dead, cannot work in water.</td>
                </tr>
            </table>

            <hr style="width: 80%; margin-left: 0;"> 
        </section>

        <!--Fourth Section-->
        <section id="section4">
            <h2>3. Iconic Examples in Media</h2>
            <p>Different genres handle power systems in unique ways:</p>

            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p><b>Nen (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hunter_%C3%97_Hunter"
                        target="_blank" title="Wikipedia">Hunter x Hunter</a>):</b>
                        Often cited as one of the most complex
                        "Hard" systems. It uses a character's life
                        energy and relies heavily on "Vows and
                        Restrictions"â€”the more dangerous a
                        restriction a user places on themselves,
                        the stronger their power becomes.</p>
                </li>

                <img src="nen.jpg" alt="Nen power system" width="500">
                <img src="hunterxhunter.jpg" alt="Hunter X Hunter">

                <li>
                    <p><b>The Force (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Star_Wars"
                        target="_blank" title="Wikipedia">Star Wars</a>):</b>
                        Originally a soft system (a mystical energy
                        field), it leaned toward a hard system with
                        the introduction of Midichlorians and
                        specific training techniques.</p>
                </li>

                <img src="the_force.jpg" alt="The Force power system" width="400">
                <img src="star_wars.jpg" alt="Star Wars" width="267">

                <li>
                    <p><b>Stand Abilities (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JoJo%27s_Bizarre_Adventure"
                        target="_blank" title="Wikipedia">JoJo's Bizarre Adventure</a>):</b>
                        A system based on specific "rules" for
                        each user. One character might only be able
                        to attack if the opponent looks at their
                        back, while another might control time for
                        exactly five seconds.</p>
                </li>

                <img src="stands.jpg" alt="Stands power system" width="500">
                <img src="jjba.jpg" alt="Jojo's Bizarre Adventure" width="582">

            </ul>

            <hr style="width: 80%; margin-left: 0;"> 
        </section>

        <!--Fifth Section-->
        <section id="section5">
            <h2>4. Sanderson's Laws of Magic</h2>
            <p>Author Brandon Sanderson, a master of power systems,
                famously coined three laws for writers: </p>

            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p><b>An author's ability to solve problems
                        with magic is DIRECTLY PROPORTIONAL to how
                        well the reader understands said magic.</b></p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p><b>Weaknesses are more interesting than
                        powers. </b>(e.g., Superman is interesting
                        because of Kryptonite, not just because he's
                        strong).</p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p><b>Expand what you already have before you
                        add something new.</b></p>
                </li>
            </ol>

            <hr style="width: 100%; margin-left: 0;"> 
        </section>

